of the [[Minneapolis-St. Paul|Twin Cities]], as well as [[St. Cloud, Minnesota]].\n\nEmmer served as a member of the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]] from 2005 until 2011 and was the Republican nominee for [[Minnesota gubernatorial election, 2010|governor in the 2010 election]]. He represented District 19B, which includes portions of [[Wright County, Minnesota|Wright]] and [[Hennepin County, Minnesota|Hennepin]] Counties and the cities of [[Otsego, Minnesota|Otsego]], [[Albertville, Minnesota|Albertville]], [[St. Michael, Minnesota|St. Michael]], [[Rockford, Minnesota|Rockford]], [[Delano, Minnesota|Delano]], [[Montrose, Minnesota|Montrose]], and [[Waverly, Minnesota|Waverly]].<ref name=\"MN legislature profile\" /> On June 5, 2013, he announced he would seek the 6th Congressional District seat being vacated by [[Michele Bachmann]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/06/05/tom-emmer-michele-bachmann_n_3389533.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Jason | last=Linkins | title=Republican To Join Race To Replace Bachmann | date=2013-06-05}}</ref> He won the November 2014 election and took office in January 2015.\n\n==Early life, education, and early political career==\nEmmer was born in [[South Bend, Indiana]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://emmer.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Biography|date=2012-12-11|work=Congressman Tom Emmer|access-date=2018-01-11|language=en}}</ref> and later moved to [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], [[Minnesota]]. He attended [[St. Thomas Academy]], an all-male, Catholic, military, college-preparatory high school in [[Mendota Heights, Minnesota|Mendota Heights]], near [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]].<ref>[http://emmerforgovernor.com/about/biography/ Biography] at Emmer's gubernatorial campaign website</ref> He then attended [[Boston College]]<ref name=\"MN legislature profile\" /> and the [[University of Alaska Fairbanks|University of Alaska at Fairbanks]],<ref name=\"pop wave\" /> where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[Political Science]] in 1984. Emmer played hockey for both schools. In 1988 he received a [[Juris Doctor]] from [[William Mitchell College of Law]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tomemmer.com/joomla/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=49&Itemid=53 |title=Emmer for Governor |publisher=Tomemmer.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-02 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBefore running for the Minnesota House of Representatives, Emmer was a member of the [[Independence, Minnesota|Independence]] and [[Delano, Minnesota|Delano]] City Councils.<ref name=\"MN legislature profile\" />\n\n==Minnesota House of Representatives==\n{{Further|Electoral history of Tom Emmer}}\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2004, incumbent Republican State Representative Dick Borrell, of Minnesota's 19B House District, decided to retire. Emmer decided to run and defeated Democrat [[Lori M. Schmidt]], an attorney, 60%\u201340%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=87708|title=Our Campaigns - MN House Seat 19B Race - Nov 02, 2004|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> In 2006, he won reelection to a second term with 61% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=272249|title=Our Campaigns - MN House Seat 19B Race - Nov 07, 2006|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-06-07}}</ref> In 2008, he won reelection to a third term with 61% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=425091 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> In 2010, he decided to retire in order to run for [[governor of Minnesota]].\n\n===Committee assignments===\nEmmer served on the Finance Committee, the Health Care and Human Services Policy and Oversight Committee, and the State and Local Government Operations Reform, Technology and Elections Committee. He was also a member of the Finance Subcommittee for the Health Care and Human Services Finance Division, and of the Health Care and Human Services Policy and Oversight Subcommittee for the Licensing Division.<ref name=\"MN legislature profile\">[http://www.leg.state.mn.us/legdb/fulldetail.asp?ID=12260 Profile of Tom Emmer] at Minnesota's legislature's website</ref>\n\n==2010 gubernatorial election==\n[[File:Emmer.jpg|thumb|right|Candidate Tom Emmer wearing an \"Emmer for Governor\" shirt in 2010]]\n{{Main|Minnesota gubernatorial election, 2010}}\n\n===Primary===\nEmmer officially announced his candidacy for [[Governor of Minnesota|governor]] of the State of Minnesota in July 2009.<ref>Duchschere, Kevin.\n[http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/50026567.html \"Delano's Emmer plans run for governor\"], ''Star Tribune'', 6 July 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://emmerforgovernor.com/ |title=Emmer's gubernatorial campaign website |publisher=Emmerforgovernor.com |date=2013-09-13 |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> In January 2010, Emmer came in second to [[Marty Seifert]] in a non-binding [[straw poll]] of Republican Party [[caucus]] participants.{{citation needed|date=November 2010}} In April 2010, Emmer announced that his [[running mate]] would be [[Metropolitan Council]] member [[Annette Meeks]]. Emmer received the endorsements of former Alaska Governor [[Sarah Palin]],<ref>[http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/04/29/sarah-palin-backs-emmer/ Sarah Palin Backs Emmer], Minnesota Public Radio News, 29 April 2010.</ref> Governor [[Tim Pawlenty]], and Lieutenant Governor [[Carol Molnau]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/01/25/molnau-emmer/ |title=Molnau backs Tom Emmer in gov's race &#124; Minnesota Public Radio NewsQ |publisher=Minnesota.publicradio.org |date=2010-01-25 |accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> On April 30, 2010, the Republican Party of Minnesota officially endorsed Emmer as its candidate for governor at the state convention in Minneapolis. His main opponent, Marty Seifert, withdrew from the race and endorsed Emmer when it became apparent that Emmer was nearing the threshold for party endorsement. On August 10, 2010, Emmer won the Republican primary with 82% of the vote, a 75-point margin over Bob Carney.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://elections.startribune.com/returns/mgovsm.html |title=2010 Elections \u2013 Governor |publisher=Star-Tribune.com |date=2010-08-11 |accessdate=2010-08-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716200339/http://elections.startribune.com/returns/mgovsm.html |archivedate=2010-07-16 |df= }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=321019 Ourcampaigns.com]</ref>\n\n===Corporate sponsorship===\nThe race attracted national attention as the \"first case in this election cycle of a company hit by national protests over a campaign donation\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hamburger |first=Tom |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-target-gays-20100817,0,6705480.story |title=Gay rights group's talks with Target break down |publisher=latimes.com |date= 2010-08-17 |accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref> Minnesota-based [[Target Corporation]] donated $150,000 to [[Minnesota Forward]], a new [[political action committee]] paying for advertising that supported Emmer's gubernatorial election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/98713934.html |title=New Ads and a New Nod in Minnesota's Governor Race |first=Rachel E. |last=Stassen-Berger |newspaper =Star Tribune |date=2010-07-18|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Emmer said he viewed Target's donation as an exercise in free speech and wanted to keep his campaign focused on economic issues.<ref>{{cite web|author=Logn, Martiga |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hCmaPDpI03kpkM76IMiBmXiEdqLwD9HIKJ180 |title=The Associated Press: Liberal groups push to exploit Target backlash |publisher=Google.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref> [[Best Buy]] also donated $100,000 to Minnesota Forward.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cummings|first=Jeanne|title=MoveOn calls for boycott of Target|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0810/41160.html|newspaper=Politico|date=August 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Results===\n{{Further|Electoral history of Tom Emmer}}\nEmmer trailed his Democratic opponent [[Mark Dayton]] by 9,000 votes in the initial general election results, a margin small enough to trigger an automatic [[election recount|recount]]. Most analysts felt it was unlikely that the Emmer campaign could overcome such a deficit in a recount.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politicsinminnesota.com/blog/2010/11/dayton-prelude-to-a-recount/ |title=Prelude to a recount |publisher=Politics in Minnesota |date= 2010-11-03|accessdate=2010-11-03}}</ref> After the recount made little difference in the results, Emmer conceded the election on December 8, 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stassen-Berger|first=Rachel E.|title=Emmer concedes; says Dayton is next governor|newspaper=Star Tribune|date=December 8, 2010|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/111500199.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120911012730/http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/111500199.html|dead-url=yes|archive-date=September 11, 2012|accessdate=December 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Post-2010 election activities==\nEmmer was a registered [[lobbyist]] in Minnesota,<ref>{{cite web|last=Helgeson |first=Baird |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/local/116203009.html |title=Emmer to lobby for effort he opposed as legislator |work=Star Tribune |date=February 14, 2011 |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> and co-hosted a morning talk radio program with Bob Davis on [[KTLK (AM)|KTLK]] in Minneapolis.\n\nIn early 2011, he ran for an open Minnesota seat on the [[Republican National Committee]], but lost that election to Hennepin County Commissioner [[Jeff Johnson (Minnesota politician)|Jeff Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/blogs/119977699.html|title= Johnson defeats Emmer for RNC Seat}}</ref>\n\nEmmer hosted a 2011 event promoting the launch of Representative [[Ron Paul]]'s presidential campaign in Minnesota.<ref name=\"paul\">{{cite web|url=http://washingtonindependent.com/113704/ron-paul-will-launch-his-minnesota-campaign-in-st-cloud|title=Ron Paul will launch his Minnesota campaign in St. Cloud|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018202107/http://washingtonindependent.com/113704/ron-paul-will-launch-his-minnesota-campaign-in-st-cloud|archivedate=2011-10-18|df=}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2014 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Minnesota, 2014#District_6}}\n{{Further|Electoral history of Tom Emmer}}\nUpon the surprise retirement of U.S. Representative [[Michele Bachmann]], Emmer was considered a possible successor in the Sixth Congressional District seat; his state house district included a large slice of the congressional district's western portion.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.kare11.com/news/article/1027684/14/Large-field-of-Republicans-will-vie-for-Bachmanns-seat |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130615203013/http://www.kare11.com/news/article/1027684/14/Large-field-of-Republicans-will-vie-for-Bachmanns-seat |dead-url=yes |archive-date=June 15, 2013 |title=Large field of Republicans will vie for Bachmann's seat |publisher=KARE 11 |date=May 29, 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-23 }}</ref> On June 5, 2013, Emmer officially announced he would seek the Republican nomination in the 2014 election. On February 4, Emmer received 67.9% of the vote in the 6th district straw poll.<ref>[https://archive.is/20140430211232/http://www.mncd6gop.com/index.php/component/content/article/4-news/latest-news/196-cd6-republicans-2014-straw-poll-results]</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.kare11.com/story/news/politics/2014/04/12/emmer-wins-endorsement-in-6th-district/7658753/ |title=Emmer wins endorsement in 6th District |publisher=KARE 11 |date=April 12, 2014 |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> On April 12, 2014, he received the Republican Party endorsement for the nomination on the first ballot with 76%, but he still faced a primary challenge from his two competitors, Anoka County Board Chairwoman [[Rhonda Sivarajah]] and former state Rep. [[Phil Krinkie]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Beldend |first=Doug |url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_25554355/republicans-endorse-emmer-run-bachmanns-6th-district-seat |title=GOP endorses Emmer for Bachmann's 6th District seat |work=Pioneer Press |date=2014-04-13 |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> Emmer received the endorsements of the [[Tea Party Express]], [[Young Americans for Liberty]]'s Liberty Action Fund, and many Minnesota legislators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.libertyaction.com/candidate/12/Tom_Emmer |title=Tom Emmer |publisher=LibertyAction |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502013405/https://www.libertyaction.com/candidate/12/Tom_Emmer |archivedate=2014-05-02 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teapartyexpress.org/7890/tea-party-express-endorses-tom-emmer-for-u-s-congress-in-minnesotas-6th-congressional-district |title=Endorses Tom Emmer for U.S. Congress in Minnesota's 6th Congressional District |publisher=Tea Party Express |date= |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> He won the primary with 73% of the vote.\n\n{{main|U.S. House elections, 2014}}\n{{Election box begin no change|title=[[Minnesota's 6th congressional district]] general election, 2014<ref>http://electionresults.sos.state.mn.us/20141104/ElecRslts.asp?M=CG&CD=06{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"clerk\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html|title=Office of the House Clerk \u2013 Electoral Statistics|publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives|accessdate=}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Tom Emmer\n  |votes      = 133,332\n  |percentage = 56.3}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Joe Perske\n  |votes      = 90,926\n  |percentage = 38.4}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Independence Party of Minnesota\n  |candidate  = John Denney\n  |votes      = 12,459\n  |percentage = 5.3}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit|Subcommittee on Financial Institutions and Consumer Credit]]\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade|Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nEmmer is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref> and the [[Congressional Western Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Abortion===\nEmmer identifies as [[pro-life]] from conception to birth.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stassen-Berger|first=Rachel E.|title=In voting records, Kelliher and Emmer mirror images |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/blogs/92708739.html|newspaper=Hot Dish Politics|date=May 3, 2010|agency=Star Tribune}}</ref>\n\n===BPA===\nIn 2009, Emmer voted against S.F. 247.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.house.leg.state.mn.us/votes/votes.asp?ls_year=86&billnum=SF0247&session_number=0&year=2009&id=1948 |title=Roll Call on S.F. NO. 247 CALENDAR FOR THE DAY Passage \u2013 Minnesota House of Representatives |publisher=House.leg.state.mn.us |date=2009-05-05 |accessdate=2014-07-07}}</ref> This Minnesota law states that as of January 1, 2010, no manufacturer, retailer, or wholesaler may sell or offer for sale in Minnesota any children's product that contains [[Bisphenol-A]], except for used children's products, which were prohibited after January 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revisor.mn.gov/bin/bldbill.php?bill=S0247.2.html&session=ls86 |title=S.F. No. 247, 2nd Engrossment \u2013 86th Legislative Session (2009-2010) |publisher=Minnesota Senate |accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref> Emmer said he voted against the law because of fear of \"increased costs.\" As well-intentioned as people may be, he said, \"they don't think about what this vote means five steps down the line.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Austin |first=Paul |url=http://www.startribune.com/yourvoices/104436274.html?elr=KArksLckD8EQDUoaEyqyP4O:DW3ckUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUKcOy9cP3DieyckcUsI |title=Five Steps Down the Line |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=2010-10-06 |accessdate=2010-11-01}}</ref>\n\n===Bullying===\nDuring an October 9, 2010, televised debate, Emmer said he would oppose legislation to combat school [[gay bullying|bullying against gay and lesbian young people]]. Emmer, who voted against anti-bullying legislation as a state lawmaker, said that teachers are most responsible for halting bullies, but suggested that the threat of lawsuits keeps them from doing so. \"I don't think we need more laws; I think we need more understanding,\" he said.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoppin|first=Jason|title=Minnesota governor hopefuls square off over bullying laws: Dayton, Horner support legislation; Emmer calls for teacher protections|url=http://www.twincities.com/politics/ci_16299917|newspaper=Pioneer Press|date=October 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Drunk driving===\nIn 2009, Emmer sponsored a bill that would shorten the period of license revocation for [[driving under the influence]] and for refusing to take a [[sobriety test]]. Additionally, though \"suspected drunken drivers [currently] face revocation before they go to court,\" Emmer's bill would have delayed revocations until after conviction.<ref name=\"startribune.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/42100987.html |title=Sponsor of DWI change has 2-ticket DWI record |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=2009-03-29 |accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref> Supporters of Emmer's bill said \"it's needed because pre-conviction revocations penalize drivers before proving they're guilty.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Doyle |work=Star Tribune |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/42034677.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU |title=Plan puts brakes on penalties for DWI |date=2009-03-27 |accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref> [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] and the head of the Minnesota DWI task force opposed the legislation<ref>Foti, Jim. [http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/42100987.html \"Sponsor of DWI change has 2-ticket DWI record\"], ''Star Tribune'', 29 March 2009.</ref> because it would allow arrested drivers to continue to drive during the time between their arrest and hearing.<ref>Scheck, Tom. [http://minnesota.publicradio.org/collections/special/columns/polinaut/archive/2010/04/seifert_keeps_u.shtml \"Seifert keeps up pressure on Emmer on DWI issue\"], Minnesota Public Radio News, 26 April 2010.</ref>\n\nEmmer's own history became an issue in relation to his bill.<ref>{{cite web|last=Helgeson |first=Baird |url=http://www.startribune.com/blogs/91846374.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU |title=Emmer DWI dustup, Day 2 |publisher=StarTribune.com |date=2010-04-22 |accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref> At age 20, Emmer received a [[driving under the influence]]-related ticket. In 1991 he pleaded guilty to careless driving while two charges for [[Driving under the influence|DWI]] and a license-plate violation were dropped.<ref>{{cite web |last=Foti |first=Jim |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/42100987.html |title=Sponsor of DWI change has 2-ticket DWI record |publisher=Star Tribune |date=2009-03-29 |accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref> Emmer denied that his own drunk driving and legal consequences played a part in the bill, stating, \"We all come to the Legislature with life experiences, but it has nothing to do with this bill.\"<ref name=\"startribune.com\"/> Emmer also stated that his sentence in 1981 should have been harsher. Had it been, Emmer felt that he \"...probably wouldn't have taken the second chance\" that led to his subsequent arrests and guilty plea in 1991.<ref>{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Doyle |work=Star Tribune |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/91775494.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU |title=Guv's race: Underwear, dirty laundry |date=2010-04-21 |accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2010, Emmer was one of three legislators not to vote on a bill that would have provided such tougher penalties for drunk drivers. He said he missed the vote when a previously scheduled lunch ran long, and that he had \"no idea\" how he would have voted on the bill, but that he \"assume[d]\" he would have supported it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Doyle|first=Pat |url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/state/93739659.html?elr=KArksUUUoDEy3LGDiO7aiU |title=Emmer, MIA on DWI vote, ignites criticism |publisher=Star Tribune|date=2010-05-13 |accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nEmmer favors repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare). After supporting the March 2017 version of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]] (a bill to repeal the ACA), he voted for it on May 4, 2017, before it had been scored by the Congressional Budget Office to determine its economic impact.\n\n===Minimum wage===\nIn 2005, as a state representative, Emmer introduced an amendment that would have eliminated Minnesota's [[Minimum wage in the United States|minimum wage law]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Bakst |first=Brian |url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9GUVRN80.htm |title=Minnesota GOP hopeful Emmer tries to fix tip jam |publisher=BusinessWeek |date=2010-07-14 |accessdate=2010-08-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818194150/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9GUVRN80.htm |archivedate=2010-08-18 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===National security===\nEmmer supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]] to temporarily curtail immigration from seven predominantly Muslim countries until better screening methods are devised, saying, \"Everybody needs to take a deep breath. There is no litmus test based on religion. The administration and I understand it has \u2014 takes the seven countries identified by the Obama administration, not this administration, as the most dangerous countries when it comes to potential terrorists.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post|accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Pharmacy conscience clause===\nEmmer has supported \"[[Conscience clause (medical)|conscience clause]]\" legislation that would allow pharmacists to refuse to dispense [[contraception]] on the basis of \"ethical, moral or legal grounds as long as the pharmacist notifies their employer in advance and the employer can ensure a patient has timely access to the drug or device\".<ref>[http://www.house.leg.state.mn.us/members/pressrelease.asp?party=2&pressid=1235&memid=12260 \u201cPharmacists\u2019 Conscience Clause\u201d Goes To House Floor], Tom Emmer's office press release, 9 March 2006.</ref>\n\n===Same-sex marriage===\nEmmer supported a state constitutional amendment banning civil recognition of [[same-sex marriage]] or its legal equivalent, stating, \"I believe marriage is the union between one man and one woman.\"<ref>[http://www.emmerforgovernor.com/issues/socialvalues/ Social Values page] at Emmer's campaign website</ref> In March 2007, Emmer introduced HF 1847, a proposed amendment to the Minnesota Constitution \"recognizing as marriage or its legal equivalent only a union between one man and one woman.\"<ref>[https://www.revisor.mn.gov/revisor/pages/search_status/status_detail.php?b=House&f=HF1847&ssn=0&y=2007 HF1847 Status in House for Legislative Session 85] Minnesota State Legislature.</ref> Voters later rejected this proposal.\n\n===State sovereignty===\nEmmer sponsored an amendment to the Minnesota Constitution that would allow the state to nullify federal laws.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kleefeld|first=Eric|title=Emmer Defends Nullification: 'Minnesotans Should Have A Say In The Laws That Govern Them'|url=http://tpmdc.talkingpointsmemo.com/2010/06/emmer-defends-nullification-minnesotans-should-have-a-say-in-the-laws-that-govern-them.php|newspaper=Talking Points Memo|date=June 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Taxes===\nEmmer strongly opposes tax increases. He has also proposed gradually reducing the state corporate tax, with the eventual goal of repealing it altogether.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmerforgovernor.com/issues/taxes/ |title=Taxes \u2013 The Issues |publisher=Emmer for Governor |date= |accessdate=2010-08-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20101021194116/http://www.emmerforgovernor.com/issues/taxes/ |archivedate=2010-10-21 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===\"Tip credit\"===\nOn July 5, 2010, after visiting a restaurant in St. Paul, Emmer was asked during a press conference if he supported a tip credit, the policy of allowing businesses to subtract [[gratuity|tips]] from a server's hourly wage. His response was \"Yes... if you didn't have a minimum wage law\", adding, \"somebody could be taking home well over one hundred thousand dollars as a server\" while the restaurant owner could be making much less.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kux4ILtTVew&feature=fvw |title=GOP's Emmer Would Like To Cut Waiter Wages |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-07-05 |accessdate=2010-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Crosby|first=Jackie|title=Emmer: Lower wages for tipped workers. The gubernatorial candidate says wages for restaurant workers are taking money from customers.|url=http://www.startribune.com/politics/97822589.html|newspaper=Star Tribune|date=July 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOne week after that press conference, Emmer announced a proposal that would exempt the first $20,000 a server makes in tips from state taxes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bakst|first=Brian |last2=Mulcahy |first2=Mike|title=Emmer's latest plan: Don't tax tips |url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/07/13/emmer-tip-taxes/|newspaper=Minnesota Public Radio|agency=Associated Press |date=July 13, 2010}}</ref> At the same press conference a protester dumped $20 in pennies in Emmer's lap.<ref>{{cite news|author=Van Denburg, Hart|title=Tom Emmer doused with 2,000 pennies by protester [VIDEO]|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2010/07/robert_erickson_2.php|date=July 15, 2010|work=City Pages|publisher=Village Voice Media|accessdate=May 4, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323113508/http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2010/07/robert_erickson_2.php|archivedate=March 23, 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEmmer's great-grandfather founded Emmer Brothers Lumber with his two brothers in 1910. It is now called Viking Forest Products LLC, an employee-owned company.<ref>[http://www.vikingforest.com/AboutUs.htm About Us] at Viking Forest's official website</ref> Emmer has seven children with Jacqueline Emmer, his wife of more than 20 years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://emmerforgovernor.com/about/biographies/tomemmer.html |title=Tom Emmer - Biographies \u2013 About the Team |publisher=Emmer for Governor |date= |accessdate=2010-08-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100926215511/http://emmerforgovernor.com/about/biographies/tomemmer.html |archivedate=2010-09-26 |df= }}</ref> He is an avid hockey player, having played in college, and continuing to coach.<ref name=\"pop wave\">Helgeson, Baird. [http://www.startribune.com/politics/local/97671799.html \"Tom Emmer: Riding a new populist wave\"], ''Star Tribune'', 11 July 2010.</ref> During the legislative session Emmer regularly rode the bus to the [[Minnesota State Capitol]].<ref name=\"pop wave\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tom Emmer}}\n* [https://emmer.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Emmer] official U.S. House site\n* [http://emmerforcongress.com/contact-us.cfm Campaign website]\n*{{DMOZ|Regional/North_America/United_States/Minnesota/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Tom_Emmer_%5BR-6%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=E000294 | votesmart=38894 | fec=H4MN06087 | congress=tom-emmer/E000294 }}\n* {{MN-legdb|12260}}\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-mn-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=Dick Borrell}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Minnesota House of Representatives]]<br>from district 19B|years=2005\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joe McDonald (politician)|Joe McDonald]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Pawlenty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Governor of Minnesota]]|years=[[Minnesota gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeff Johnson (Minnesota politician)|Jeff Johnson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michele Bachmann]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Minnesota|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Minnesota's 6th congressional district]]|years=2015\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Debbie Dingell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority